=========================================
C++17 std::variant
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::variant?

std::variant is a C++17 type-safe union that can hold one value from a fixed set of types at a time.

It is a safer replacement for C-style unions.

Header

#include <variant>

Syntax

std::variant<T1, T2, T3...>

-----------------------------------------

2. Why was std::variant introduced?

Before C++

union Data
{
    int x;
    float y;
};

Problem

• No type safety
• You must manually track which type is active
• Accessing wrong type = Undefined Behavior
• No compiler protection

-----------------------------------------

3. C++17 Solution

#include <variant>
using namespace std;

variant<int, string, double> data;

data = 10;

cout << get<int>(data);

data = string("Hello");

cout << get<string>(data);

Output

10
Hello

-----------------------------------------

4. What is happening internally?

variant stores:

• One of the possible types
• A tag (index) indicating which type is active

Example

variant<int, string>

data = 10;

Internally:

index = 0
value = 10

data = "Hello";

index = 1
value = "Hello"

-----------------------------------------

5. Accessing values

Method 1: get<T>

cout << get<int>(data);

⚠ Must know the correct active type

Throws exception if wrong type is accessed

-----------------------------------------

Method 2: get_if (safer)

if(auto p = get_if<int>(&data))
{
    cout << *p;
}

-----------------------------------------

Method 3: holds_alternative

if(holds_alternative<int>(data))
{
    cout << get<int>(data);
}

-----------------------------------------

6. Changing value

data = 10;
data = 3.14;
data = string("Hello");

Only ONE value is active at a time.

-----------------------------------------

7. Example

#include <iostream>
#include <variant>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    variant<int,string,double> v;

    v = 10;
    cout << get<int>(v) << endl;

    v = "Hello";
    cout << get<string>(v) << endl;

    v = 3.14;
    cout << get<double>(v) << endl;
}

Output

10
Hello
3.14

-----------------------------------------

8. What happens if wrong type is accessed?

variant<int,string> v = 10;

cout << get<string>(v);

Throws:

std::bad_variant_access

-----------------------------------------

9. safer visit() method (VERY IMPORTANT ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐)

#include <iostream>
#include <variant>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    variant<int,string> v = "Hello";

    visit([](auto&& val)
    {
        cout << val;
    }, v);
}

Output

Hello

visit automatically handles all types safely.

-----------------------------------------

10. Difference: union vs variant

C union

• Unsafe
• No type tracking
• Manual control
• Undefined behavior risk

std::variant

• Type-safe
• Compiler tracks active type
• Safe access methods
• No undefined behavior (if used correctly)

-----------------------------------------

11. Advantages

• Type safety
• No undefined behavior
• Better than union
• Works with complex types (string, class, etc.)
• Compile-time type checking

-----------------------------------------

12. Where is std::variant used?

• State machines
• Parsers
• JSON handling
• Compilers
• Event systems
• Message passing systems
• APIs with multiple return types

-----------------------------------------

13. Interview Questions

Q. What is std::variant?

Answer

std::variant is a C++17 type-safe union that can hold one value from a set of specified types at a time.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced std::variant?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. How is variant different from union?

Answer

union is unsafe and does not track the active type, while std::variant is type-safe and keeps track of which type is currently active.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What happens if wrong type is accessed?

Answer

It throws std::bad_variant_access.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is visit()?

Answer

visit() applies a callable to the currently active type in the variant and is the safest way to access variant values.

-----------------------------------------

14. Interview Explanation (30 Seconds)

"std::variant is a C++17 type-safe union that can store one value from multiple types. Unlike a traditional union, 
it keeps track of the active type internally and prevents undefined behavior. Values are accessed using get<T>, 
get_if, or the safer visit function. It is commonly used in state machines, parsers, and APIs that need to return multiple possible types."

